Step 1: Set up the project
Follow the steps I mentioned earlier to set up your React project. Once you have your project ready, open the project directory in your code editor.

Step 2: Create the components
Inside the "src" folder, create a new folder called "components". In this folder, create two files: "TodoList.js" and "TodoItem.js". 

In "TodoList.js", add the following code:
```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const TodoList = () => {
  const [todos, setTodos] = useState([]);

  return (
    <div>
      {/* Render the list of todos */}
    </div>
  );
};

export default TodoList;
```

In "TodoItem.js", add the following code:
```jsx
import React from 'react';

const TodoItem = ({ text, completed }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      {/* Render an individual todo item */}
    </div>
  );
};

export default TodoItem;
```

Step 3: Implement the state
Inside the "TodoList.js" component, modify the code as follows:
```jsx
const [todos, setTodos] = useState([]);
```

This creates a state variable called "todos" and a function called "setTodos" to manage the list of to-do items. Initialize it as an empty array.

Step 4: Render the list
Inside the "TodoList.js" component, modify the code as follows:
```jsx
return (
  <div>
    {todos.map((todo, index) => (
      <TodoItem key={index} text={todo.text} completed={todo.completed} />
    ))}
  </div>
);
```

This maps over the list of to-do items from the state ("todos") and renders a "TodoItem" component for each item. We pass the necessary props, "text" and "completed", to each "TodoItem" component.

Step 5: Add new to-do items
Inside the "TodoList.js" component, add the following code:
```jsx
const [newTodo, setNewTodo] = useState('');

const handleAddTodo = () => {
  if (newTodo.trim() !== '') {
    setTodos([...todos, { text: newTodo, completed: false }]);
    setNewTodo('');
  }
}

return (
